      <h3>Hypertext</h3>
      <p>
        The term "hypertext" was coined by Ted Nelson in the 1960s, as discussed in Smith & Weiss (1988). Its conceptual foundation can be traced back to Vannevar Bush's idea of "the memex" in 1945. This device was designed to emulate the associative structure of human memory (Vannevar Bush, 1945). Unlike traditional, linear documents, hypertext enables a complex, networked organisation of information. Each node in this network can store various data types, ranging from text and graphics to audio and video. As a result, hypertext becomes an interactive and dynamic tool for discovering information (Smith & Weiss, 1988). Hypertext has transformed the way we handle and interact with information in digital contexts. It enables real-time updates and dynamic linking, making it a foundational internet technology. Because of its adaptability and flexibility, its uses have expanded beyond online browsing to academic research, software development, and other industries requiring difficult information management.
      </p>
      <img src="../assets/Figure6.png" alt="Simple hypertext visualisation" />
