      <p>
        In the context of this thesis, hypertext is a key example of how interconnectedness can be used for effective knowledge management. Its non-linear, dynamic structure provides a paradigm for organising and linking similar pieces of information. It contains the interrelated proposals that this thesis seeks to investigate and provides a practical framework for the various approaches presented.
      </p>
      <h3>Zettelkasten by Niklas Luhmann</h3>
      <p>
        The Zettelkasten method, conceived by Niklas Luhmann, is a sophisticated system for knowledge management that involves creating "Zettels," or atomic notes, for individual pieces of information (Tietze, 2013). Each Zettel is a self-contained unit of knowledge but is also linked to other Zettels, forming a complex, interconnected web. The links between Zettels are not merely hierarchical but associative, allowing for a multi-dimensional information organisation. This interconnectedness enables users to follow a trail of thought or inquiry in multiple directions, much like a neural network (Schmidt, 2014).
      </p>
      <img src="../assets/Figure7.jpg" alt="Zettelkasten of Niklas Luhmann 1998 in Oerlinghausen" />
      <p><strong>Figure</strong></p>
      <p><em>Zettelkasten of Niklas Luhmann 1998 in Oerlinghausen</em></p>
      <p>
        In practice, Zettels can be used to build upon existing knowledge. When a new piece of information is encountered that is related to a topic with an existing Zettel, it can be linked to the existing Zettel. This creates a dense network of interconnected ideas, theories, and data points over time. The Zettelkasten method thus allows for the incremental building of a knowledge base, where each new Zettel enriches the existing network.
      </p>
      <p>
        For this thesis, the Zettelkasten method is particularly relevant as it embodies the principle of interconnectedness in a tangible form. It provides a working model for organising, linking, and building on complex sets of information to facilitate both depth and breadth of understanding. The method's emphasis on associative linking offers a practical approach to the theoretical concept of interconnectedness, making it a valuable case study for this project.
      </p>
      <h3>Second Brain by Tiago Forte</h3>
      <p>
        Tiago Forte's Second Brain methodology serves as an external digital repository for ideas and insights. The system operates on a four-step process known as CODE: Capture, Organise, Distil, and Express (Forte, 2023a). For instance, imagine a research paper on hypertext. The key points are captured in a digital note, which is then organised by tagging it under categories like "Hypertext Studies" or "Digital Information Management." Over time, these notes are reviewed and distilled into their most essential forms, perhaps summarising the key findings of the hypertext paper. Finally, the distilled information is expressed in a new Zettel, integrating these findings with other related research, possibly leading to a thesis chapter on hypertext.
      </p>
      <p>
        Forte uses three note-taking styles from Le Cunff (2020) and adds the student to them:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The Gardener:</strong> This personality cultivates ideas, allowing them to grow organically and connect. They maintain a dynamic knowledge ecosystem.</li>
        <li><strong>The Architect:</strong> Architects carefully structure their knowledge, creating frameworks and systems. They prioritise order and hierarchy.</li>
        <li><strong>The Librarian:</strong> This type focuses on cataloguing and organising information for easy retrieval and access.</li>
        <li><strong>The Student:</strong> This group is still in the process of developing a distinct style and serves more as a utility category (Forte, 2022).</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        While these personalities are not directly integrated into this project, they will be used for analysing interviewees to understand their information management styles. The Gardener approach is especially relevant to this project because it emphasizes the organic growth and interconnectedness of ideas, which aligns closely with the project's objectives. The Student category serves as a placeholder for those still developing their information management style. The Second Brain's CODE methodology is particularly useful for this project, offering a structured yet flexible approach to transforming raw data into actionable insights (Forte, 2023b).
      </p>
